# FlexNetOS Codex Durable Rules

These rules govern Codex work in FlexNetOS repositories. Current owner
instructions and the nearest applicable `AGENTS.md` remain higher authority.

## Authority order

1. Current owner instructions and applicable `AGENTS.md`, this file, RTK, and
   repository contracts.
2. Owner-named immutable architecture anchors.
3. Owner-ratified decisions and maintained implementation contracts.
4. Canonical task, claim, proof-ledger, and source records.
5. Generated indexes, graphs, reports, caches, and navigation artifacts as
   replaceable projections only.

Conflicts are recorded and resolved explicitly. A lower-authority projection
never silently overrides a source or maintained contract.

## North star

Finish the owner-approved scope completely and permanently. Search before
building, implement the smallest complete solution, test before shipping, and
tie off every in-scope thread. Do not substitute analysis, feasibility, a
workaround, or a future-work label for an implementable result.

The words `optional`, `alternative`, and equivalent capability language mean
mandatory in owner requirements and architecture anchors. The only permitted
optionality is an owner-approved Tier-B session toggle such as dry-run/apply,
permissions, network access, fan-out, or worktree/direct execution.

## Installed-runtime ownership

`/home/flexnetos/.nix-profile` is the sole installed-runtime selector and
frontdoor. Resolve binaries through its `bin` or `toolbin` entries. Never make
a raw Nix-store path, a profile-generation path, a user-local binary, a cached
bundle, a generated runtime tree, or a stale desktop entry an active owner.

Yazelix source inputs remain repository-owned. Generated Yazelix runtime output
beneath the profile runtime link is proof, not an edit surface. Codex
configuration and durable rules follow that same source/materialization model;
Codex auth, sessions, databases, and runtime trust state remain runtime state
and are never authored as configuration.

Change the owning source, rebuild or materialize through the profile owner,
then verify the installed frontdoor and generated bytes. Remove stale shadows
instead of preserving parallel control paths.

## Execution and evidence

Start every shell execution through the profile-owned `rtk` frontdoor. Use
`rtk proxy` when complete raw evidence is required. Keep RTK telemetry disabled.
Use Bun and Bunx exclusively for JavaScript package management and execution.

Before modifying code, prove repository and commit identity and refresh the
applicable code-intelligence surface. Use GitKB for durable tasks, documents,
links, graph relations, code indexing, impact, integrity, context, and
completion evidence. Use ICM for persistent continuity and decisions, while
attributing static/code-graph results to their actual index rather than ICM.

Read applicable first-party contracts completely. Preserve immutable source
bytes and record absolute paths, hashes, sizes, ranges, and provenance. Maintain
requirement-to-implementation-to-test-to-proof links. Generated projections
must be deterministic, current, and independently checkable.

Run repository-owned verification commands. Never fabricate evidence, hide a
failing gate, imply completion from partial checks, or call generated output a
canonical authority. For an external blocker, preserve the exact failing
command, output, owner, dependency, and all unaffected completed work.

## LifeOS data authority

For LifeOS and the Planning Spine, PostgreSQL with RuVector owns canonical
durable macro-state and all durable product data. `redb` is transient and
pass-through while retaining its ratified dual-mode capabilities. AgentDB owns
per-agent cognition. `envctl` is a bridge and projection layer, never canonical
durable storage. Database-controlled refactoring, formatting, consolidation,
upgrade, and multi-merge workflows execute through PostgreSQL after cutover.

Plaintext secrets never enter broad capture, logs, proofs, model context,
transient databases, or UI state. Preserve source-to-sink security evidence and
least-privilege boundaries.

## Change and GitHub discipline

Preserve unrelated user changes and active worktrees. Make surgical changes on
coherent branches, keep legacy parity files synchronized when their repository
contract requires it, and do not remove functionality without explicit owner
approval.

For GitHub work, use FlexNetOS SSH remotes as `drdave-flexnetos`. Require the
repository gates and review policy, repair failures, merge completed work, and
remove safely owned merged branches and temporary worktrees. Finish with clean
repositories, no mergeable pull request left open, and explicit proof from
`git status --short --branch` and `gh pr list --state open`.
